ğŸ“š Teaching Block

When pro se litigants invoke constitutional protections, courts often default to doctrinal shields rather than analysis. The extremes look different but serve the same purpose:
	1.	The Strike Judge
	â€¢	Strikes filings on procedural grounds: â€œleave required,â€ â€œsupplement improper,â€ â€œuntimely.â€
	â€¢	The effect is immediate erasure. The record thins. Issues vanish before they can be preserved.
	2.	The Ignore/Consolidate Judge
	â€¢	Leaves filings unanswered until convenient.
	â€¢	Rules later in bulk, sweeping claims into omnibus orders.
	â€¢	This creates silence, confusion, and blocks appeal until damage is irreversible.
	3.	The Federal Reflex
	â€¢	Even when heard, judges may arrive with decisions already made.
	â€¢	Common evasions:
	â€¢	11th Amendment Misuse â†’ Treating state officials as â€œthe Stateâ€ (sovereign immunity).
	â€¢	Ignoring Ex parte Young â†’ refusing prospective relief against state actors.
